    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1885-07-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1885-07-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="241" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d241">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 241.</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Foulk</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                    the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Seoul,
                                Corea</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1885-07-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">July</hi> 5, 1885</date>. (Received August
                            15.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 193.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that a Corean
                        gentleman, who had been instructed as to methods of searching for coal-beds
                        by an American merchant, has returned from a journey of inspection, and
                        reports his having found large beds of coal near the sea-coast, on the
                        Ta-tong River, west coast of Corea. Several loads of the coal have arrived
                        in junks at Chemulpo, and there the coal was tested on board the U. S. S.
                        Alert, proving to be of better quality than that of Japan, although that
                        tested was but surface scrapings. A second coal-bed has been discovered some
                        30 miles south of Chemulpo, on the coast.</p>
                <p>Steps are being taken to develop both these beds, an American to work the
                        first and a Chinese company the second.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>GEORGE C. FOULK,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Ensign, U. S. Navy,
                                Chargé d’Affaires ad interim.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
